            <td>Vanguard</td>
            <td class="highlight-col">0.03%</td>
            <td>$1.51T</td>
            <td>$612.5</td>
            <td>16.95%</td>
            <td>14.15%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="highlight-ticker">IVV</td>
            <td>iShares</td>
            <td class="highlight-col">0.03%</td>
            <td>$750.65B</td>
            <td>$668.95</td>
            <td>16.96%</td>
            <td>14.16%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="highlight-ticker">SPY</td>
            <td>State Street</td>
            <td class="highlight-col">0.09%</td>
            <td>$698.27B</td>
            <td>$666.06</td>
            <td>16.87%</td>
            <td>14.08%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="section-title">Visualizing the Fee Difference</h2>
    <p>While a few basis points (0.02% vs 0.03% vs 0.09%) may seem microscopic, they compound over a lifetime of investing. This chart illustrates the impact of expense ratios on a hypothetical $100,000 initial investment over 30 years, assuming a gross 10% annualized return.</p>

    <div class="chart-container">
      <canvas id="feeChart"></canvas>
    </div>

    <h2 class="section-title">Top 10 Holdings</h2>
    <p>Because SPLG is a market-cap weighted index fund tracking the S&P 500, its top holdings are identical to VOO, SPY, and IVV. As of 2026, the S&P 500 is heavily concentrated in mega-cap technology stocks.</p>

    <div class="table-container" style="max-width: 600px;">
